#Text=Swedish phrasebook
#Text=Swedish ( svenska ) is a North Germanic language , closely related to Norwegian and Danish ( and through them , related to Icelandic and Faroese ) and strongly influenced by Low German .
#Text=Spoken by over 9 million people , Swedish is the national language of Sweden and the official language of the Åland Islands .
#Text=It is also an official language of Finland ( along with Finnish ) , though only the mother tongue for about 6 percent of Finns , mostly concentrated in some coastal areas .

#Text=Like for instance British and American English , there are differences between Swedish spoken in Sweden ( rikssvenska ) and Swedish spoken in Finland ( finlandssvenska ) , in pronunciation , grammar and vocabulary , partly due to influence from Finnish in the latter , but also due to it retaining some archaic features .
#Text=Finland-Swedish is less tonal , slightly more phonetic and like in Finnish the ' r ' is always trilled .

#Text=There are dialectal differences inside Finland and Sweden too , most notably the Swedish spoken in Scania reminds of Danish to some extent , but Swedish speakers with different dialects seldom have difficulties understanding each other .
#Text=Some archaic dialects of rural Ostrobothnia are incomprehensible , but the speakers will switch to normal Swedish when talking to non-locals .
#Text=As Swedish is a Germanic language , speakers of other Germanic languages like German , Dutch or even English will be able to recognise many cognates .
#Text=While practically everyone in Sweden under the age of 70 can speak some English , most younger people fluently , trying out some words of Swedish is always appreciated .
#Text=The same is true about the Swedish speaking in Finland – but you should probably stick to English or Finnish with people whose first language is Finnish .
#Text=Vowels
#Text=Swedish is notorious for its extra vowel sounds , giving Swedish nine ( ! ) different vowels .
#Text=Most are pronounced differently than English , and some do n't even have a true English equivalent ; some may be close , but sound like a combination of two vowel sounds .
#Text=This can be very confusing , but you probably wo n't hear enough Swedish to know the difference , as they can be very slight .
#Text=If you do n't get it exactly , you may still be understood .
#Text=All vowels can be pronounced short or long which means that Swedish has 17 different vowel sounds ( short e and short ä is the same ) .
#Text=Please note : in Swedish ' Y ' is a vowel and not a consonant . Å , Ä and Ö are letters in their own right , in the end of the alphabet past Z.
#Text=a : like ' a ' in " father .

column1: #Text=Similar to å in Danish .
#Text=ä : identical to the ä in German ( sounds like an " e " as in " bet " .
#Text=Pronounced with more bass if preceding r. Corresponds to æ in Danish and Norwegian .
#Text=ö : Same as in German .
#Text=Pronounced with more bass if preceding r. Corresponds to ø in Danish and Norwegian .
#Text=The pronunciation of u and y varies quite a lot between regions ; all native speakers make a clear distinction , although the u of somebody may be close to y of somebody else .
#Text=Consonants
#Text=Consonants are closer to English , but some combinations can be downright tricky , i.e. ' sj ' in " sjutton .

#Text= Some pronunciations depend on the vowel following it , and so the vowels are divided into " soft " and " hard " vowels .

column1: #Text=c : like ' c ' in " cat " , sometimes ' s ' like the first c in circus ; a ' ch ' combination is sometimes pronounced like English ' sh ' , but pronounced like a ' k ' in the word och .
#Text=d : like ' d ' in " dog "
#Text=f : like ' f ' in " for "

#Text=g : like ' g ' in " go " , when preceding a hard vowel , like ' y ' in " yellow " when preceding a soft vowel . A ' gn ' pronunciation is pronounced like an English ' g ' , except for when it follows a vowel , in which case it is pronounced ' ng+n .
#Text='
#Text=h : like ' h ' in " help " .
#Text=A superfluous silent ' h ' is common in names ( e. g. Elisabet and Elisabeth are pronounced the same ) .
#Text=j : like ' y ' in " yell , " and if there is a d , g , or h before a ' j ' then that letter is silent .
#Text=k : like ' k ' in " king " before a hard vowel , like ' sh ' before a soft one .
#Text=' Kj ' is pronounced ' sh ' as well
#Text=l : like ' l ' in " love , " but ' lj ' is pronounced like a ' y '
#Text=m : like ' m ' in " mother "
#Text=n : like ' n ' in " nice " , like ' ng ' in " song " when preceding k
